{"id": "27504", "revid": "25771421", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=27504", "title": "Chilanik's Chain", "text": "Chilanik's Chain\u00a0is a &lt;a href=\"Legendary%20Items\"&gt;Legendary&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Mighty%20Belts\"&gt;Mighty Belt&lt;/a&gt; for the\u00a0\u00a0in\u00a0\"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". It requires &lt;a href=\"character%20level\"&gt;character level&lt;/a&gt; 31 to drop.\nThe special property is designed specifically for PvP in groups: in a usual game, it may be useful for retreating quickly for the entire party."}
{"id": "54265", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=54265", "title": "Child of Bul-Kathos", "text": ""}
{"id": "17941", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=17941", "title": "Children of Bul-Kathos", "text": "The Children of Bul-Kathos, better known as Barbarians and sometimes referred to as \"Northmen\", \"Arreat's Children\" or the \"Broken People,\" are a collection of tribes who once lived on &lt;a href=\"Mount%20Arreat\"&gt;Mount Arreat&lt;/a&gt; and protected the &lt;a href=\"Worldstone\"&gt;Worldstone&lt;/a&gt;.\nHistory.\nThe Vigil.\nThe Barbarian tribes' origins lie in a time before recorded history. It is written in the \"&lt;a href=\"Sc%C3%A9al%20Fada\"&gt;Sc\u00e9al Fada&lt;/a&gt;\" that it was &lt;a href=\"Bul-Kathos\"&gt;Bul-Kathos&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Fiacla-G%C3%A9ar\"&gt;Fiacla-G\u00e9ar&lt;/a&gt; who agreed that in order to safeguard the Worldstone, their people would have to devote the entirety of their lives to the task. Their ideas on how to best approach the task differed however, and while G\u00e9ar took his &lt;a href=\"druid\"&gt;followers&lt;/a&gt; to &lt;a href=\"Scosglen\"&gt;Scosglen&lt;/a&gt;, Bul-Kathos gathered the Barbarian tribes of the &lt;a href=\"Northern%20Steppes\"&gt;Northern Steppes&lt;/a&gt;. Tasked with defending the Worldstone, Barbarian culture was built around its defense. To better protect their lands, they adopted a nomadic lifestyle constantly moving around the Northern Steppes and possessing few permanent settlements.\nThe Samuren Empire and Worrusk.\n\"Note that the following events are not necessarily in chronological order.\"\nWorrusk.\nOriginally the Barbarians roamed the entire western continent of &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;Sanctuary&lt;/a&gt;. During a period of inter-tribal warfare, the Barbarian &lt;a href=\"Worusk\"&gt;Worusk&lt;/a&gt; was able to unite them and for a brief time, the Barbarians were united under a single king. The Barbarian kingdom stretched as far to the jungles of the south. Under his reign, the &lt;a href=\"Council%20of%20Elders\"&gt;Council of Elders&lt;/a&gt; was formed in &lt;a href=\"Harrogath\"&gt;Harrogath&lt;/a&gt;. Even after his death, the Council remained as a governing body.\nThe Samuren Empire.\nAt some point the Barbarian tribes (or at least the &lt;a href=\"Oxen%20Tribe\"&gt;Oxen Tribe&lt;/a&gt; came into conflict with the &lt;a href=\"Samuren%20Empire\"&gt;Samuren Empire&lt;/a&gt;, which was bent on conquering the north. The &lt;a href=\"Samurenian\"&gt;Samurenian&lt;/a&gt;s interred captured Barbarians in labor camps. The Barbarians ultimately prevailed, as &lt;a href=\"Raekor\"&gt;Raekor&lt;/a&gt; led them to victory, sacking the empire's capital.\nThe Coming of Rakkis.\nDuring the &lt;a href=\"Timeline%231245\"&gt;mid-tenth century&lt;/a&gt;, a crusade was launched from the &lt;a href=\"Kehjistan\"&gt;East&lt;/a&gt; to bring the &lt;a href=\"Zakarum\"&gt;Zakarum&lt;/a&gt; faith to the lands of the West. Battling against the &lt;a href=\"Sons%20of%20Rakkis\"&gt;Sons of Rakkis&lt;/a&gt;, the Barbarians lost control of much of the West. However, &lt;a href=\"Rakkis\"&gt;Rakkis&lt;/a&gt;'s forces could never conquer the Northern Steppes.\nVigil Continued.\nThe Children of Bul-Kathos kept themselves isolated from the rest of Sanctuary, and while they would permit some trade with the outside world, this would only occur at the border of their territory. All intrusions into the territory surrounding Mount Arreat were forbidden, and warriors from the northern tribes were quick to thwart any incursions from foes. Because of their savagery in battle, the people of the &lt;a href=\"Western%20Kingdoms\"&gt;Western Kingdoms&lt;/a&gt; frequently called them \"barbarians,\" and regarded them as bloodthirsty invaders. Regardless, the Barbarians stood ready, as the &lt;a href=\"Prophecies%20of%20the%20Final%20Day\"&gt;Prophecies of the Final Day&lt;/a&gt; declared that a time would come when &lt;a href=\"Burning%20Hells\"&gt;Hell&lt;/a&gt; would surge forward, seeking to undo the works of &lt;a href=\"the%20Ancients\"&gt;the Ancients&lt;/a&gt; in a &lt;a href=\"Uileloscadh%20M%C3%B3r\"&gt;final conflict&lt;/a&gt;.\nUileloscadh M\u00f3r.\n\"Baal comes... and destruction follows him like a storm.\"\n\u2014 &lt;a href=\"Caldra\"&gt;Caldra&lt;/a&gt;'s final words\nWhen news of &lt;a href=\"Diablo\"&gt;Diablo&lt;/a&gt;'s re-emergence at &lt;a href=\"Tristram\"&gt;Tristram&lt;/a&gt; spread, a small number of Barbarian warriors began roving the lands outside the Steppes, prepared for war and seeking information regarding the recent activities of the Prime Evils. &lt;a href=\"Barbarian%20%28Diablo%20II%29\"&gt;One of their number&lt;/a&gt; made contact with a group of other heroes, and the &lt;a href=\"Horadric\"&gt;Horadric&lt;/a&gt; scholar &lt;a href=\"Deckard%20Cain\"&gt;Deckard Cain&lt;/a&gt;. The group tracked Diablo from &lt;a href=\"Khanduras\"&gt;Khanduras&lt;/a&gt; to &lt;a href=\"Aranoch\"&gt;Aranoch&lt;/a&gt;, the jungles of &lt;a href=\"Kurast\"&gt;Kurast&lt;/a&gt;, and even the fires of &lt;a href=\"Burning%20Hells\"&gt;Hell&lt;/a&gt; itself. Diablo and &lt;a href=\"Mephisto\"&gt;Mephisto&lt;/a&gt; were defeated, but &lt;a href=\"Baal\"&gt;Baal&lt;/a&gt;, the final &lt;a href=\"Prime%20Evil\"&gt;Prime Evil&lt;/a&gt;, remained unaccounted for. The Lord of Destruction headed north, building an &lt;a href=\"Army%20of%20Destruction\"&gt;army&lt;/a&gt; as he did so, intent on corrupting the Worldstone. The Prophecies of the Final Day had been fulfilled. Uileloschadh M\u00f3r had begun.\nBy all accounts, the Barbarians fought ferociously, living up to their reputation as Sanctuary's hardiest warriors. Yet it was not enough. At &lt;a href=\"Daken-Shar\"&gt;Daken-Shar&lt;/a&gt;, the Barbarian defenders were eradicated almost to the &lt;a href=\"Renit%20the%20Dark%20Stalker\"&gt;last man&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a href=\"Sescheron\"&gt;Sescheron&lt;/a&gt;, their capital, was sacked. Eventually, all that stood between Baal and the &lt;a href=\"Arreat%20Summit\"&gt;Arreat Summit&lt;/a&gt; was &lt;a href=\"Harrogath\"&gt;Harrogath&lt;/a&gt; and its defenders. In desperation, the town's elders sacrificed themselves as part of a warding spell to create a protective barrier around the settlement. Only &lt;a href=\"Nihlathak\"&gt;Nihlathak&lt;/a&gt; survived.\nBaal's forces lay siege, and Barbarian defenders suffered for it. The heroes who had slain Baal's brothers arrived however, and did all they could to break the siege. However, their efforts were overshadowed by Nihlathak's actions, who had bartered the &lt;a href=\"Relic%20of%20the%20Ancients\"&gt;Relic of the Ancients&lt;/a&gt; to Baal in exchange for Harrogath being spared. With the relic, Baal could scale Mount Arreat unopposed by its guardians.\nBoth Nihlathak and Baal met their end at the hands of the heroes, but Baal had already corrupted the Worldstone. To save humanity, the &lt;a href=\"archangel\"&gt;archangel&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Tyrael\"&gt;Tyrael&lt;/a&gt; was forced to destroy it. Through his actions, humanity was spared damnation, and Baal's army destroyed, but the cost to the Barbarian tribes was horrific. The resulting explosion leveled Mount Arreat and devastated the surrounding area. Toxic clouds of ash and arcane dust fell over the Steppes, the damage so horrific that it became known as the &lt;a href=\"Dreadlands\"&gt;Dreadlands&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe Aftermath.\nIn the years following Arreat's destruction, the peoples of Sanctuary began to understand the long and noble history the Barbarian culture once possessed, and became acknowledged. But with the destruction of the Worldstone and devastation of their homeland, many Barbarians lost faith. Some became aimless, haunted by their past, traveling from place to place without honor or direction. The majority of the Barbarians remained within the Dreadlands (the former Northern Steppes), but small groups from the &lt;a href=\"Oxen%20Tribe\"&gt;Oxen&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Crane%20Tribe\"&gt;Crane&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Bear%20Tribe\"&gt;Bear&lt;/a&gt; tribes left, intent on finding a new home. Some Barbarians left Arreat to battle evil, in in atonement for their failed stewardship. When Barbarian tribes left Mount Arreat, their forlorn songs could be heard across forests. More than anything, they sang of mourning.\nOf the tribes that remained in the Dreadlands, fortunes were mixed. Some tribes fell into regression, becoming akin to unreasoning beasts and, in some cases, even cannibals. Some still honored the harsh snows of Arreat's summit and prowled the outskirts of its &lt;a href=\"Arreat%20Crater\"&gt;crater&lt;/a&gt;, maintaining enclaves in isolated fortifications. They recalled being handed axes and spears at an age when city children were clinging to their toys...and they burnt with shame at the failure of their people. These Barbarians strove to find a new purpose for themselves in a changed world, and would crush any who stand in their way.\nA number of scattered Barbarian clans remained on the &lt;a href=\"Frozen%20Tundra\"&gt;Frozen Tundra&lt;/a&gt;, but they were scattered and isolated. They battled against the remnants of Baal's army, but they could either stand united or die divided. It was feared that if these tribes fell, the Army of Destruction would again be able to threaten &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;Sanctuary&lt;/a&gt;.\nAmong the Barbarians who left their homeland, &lt;a href=\"Barbarian%20%28Diablo%20III%29\"&gt;one of them&lt;/a&gt; took note of the evil that had taken root in Sanctuary. They saw an opportunity to give the Barbarians hope, a reason to fight, and a reason to live.\nThe Great Enmity.\nDuring the &lt;a href=\"Great%20Enmity\"&gt;Great Enmity&lt;/a&gt;, a few Barbarians served the &lt;a href=\"Cathedral%20of%20Light\"&gt;Cathedral of Light&lt;/a&gt;. They had little fear of death, pain, or evil, believing their fate written by &lt;a href=\"Inarius\"&gt;Inarius&lt;/a&gt; himself.\nCulture.\nBarbarians eschew the use of &lt;a href=\"magic\"&gt;magic&lt;/a&gt; and technology, as they believe the use of such devices will only weaken their resolve. Barbarians have frequently expressed disdain for magic, and those who wield it. Renowned for their combat prowess and arrogant demeanor, Barbarians appear to be perpetually girt for battle. Through harsh conditioning, Barbarians excel in physical combat and can perform tremendous feats of strength. Their physical strength is further strengthened by the primal energies of the land, which they have learned to harness. Never shying from a brawl, mighty ground stomps, leaping attacks and crushing blows leave enemies dead in their tracks, and survivors cowering in fear. Barbarians are not hindered when disarmed in battle, their fists are viable weapons. Barbarians revel in the chance to test their might against worthy foes, forging their reputations in the blood of their vanquished enemies. \nWhen a barbarian rages, they don't lose control. They vow to end their enemy and consider nothing else until that end is achieved. Most Barbarians find their inner fury before adulthood. Those who come to their rages later in life often blame a hidden \"second self.\"\nBarbarians sometimes forego armor, as it causes gruesome wounds when struck by a heavy weapon (which they usually use). Barbarians of the Dreadlands were wont to brawl with one another, and even the faintest violence could beget escalation. To swing only once was considered an insult.\nThe Barbarians hunted &lt;a href=\"aurochs\"&gt;aurochs&lt;/a&gt;, and used their fur as clothing. Some believe that the Barbarians hunted the aurochs to extinction; that the reason for their size and strength is because the Northerners of old fed on aurochs flesh.\nPrior to the deeds of Raekor, Barbarian women, while still highly regarded as warriors, were still seen by their male peers as being inferior to men on the field of battle. Raekor's deeds, with her being the first female to gain the coveted title of warmaster, changed this perception. However, even by &lt;a href=\"Timeline%231263\"&gt;1263&lt;/a&gt;, Barbarian warriors were primarily male.\nDuring their vigil, Barbarian trials began at childhood; skinning ferocious beasts, climbing windswept cliffs and carrying weapons heavy enough to make a southern soldier weep. They are trained in hand-to-hand combat from a young age. As a result, their combat and survival skills are unparalleled throughout Sanctuary. Exposed to the elements of their homeland, Barbarian skin has been toughened to match the resilience of leather, and can withstand attacks that would slay lesser mortals. It is said that Barbarians are incapable of feeling cold.\nBecause of the scarcity of food in their homeland, Barbarians are able to consume species of plants that would kill normal &lt;a href=\"human\"&gt;men&lt;/a&gt;. Likewise, Barbarians regularly scavenged the bodies of their falls, due to the scarcity of materials in their homeland. \nBarbarians appear to have a numbering system that is represented by runes. They have their own language. For instance, the &lt;a href=\"Army%20of%20Destruction\"&gt;Army of Destruction&lt;/a&gt; was called \"Ahjad-Den.\"\nBarbarians practice marriage, the events being known for their rowdiness. \nA Barbarian practice called the Sorrowsong exists. These are apparently composed for those who have deceased or at the least, departed a tribe.\nAn individual not of Barbarian blood may still be given the honorific of \"blood brother,\" if they have ingratiated themselves with a tribe.\nReligion.\nBarbarians are a spiritual people, and their faith system is/was based around &lt;a href=\"Bul-Kathos\"&gt;Bul-Kathos&lt;/a&gt; (the \"immortal king\") and &lt;a href=\"the%20Ancients\"&gt;the Ancients&lt;/a&gt;, a trio of &lt;a href=\"nephalem\"&gt;nephalem&lt;/a&gt; spirits who guarded Mount Arreat. Per the tenets of their belief system, every Barbarian in life was expected to defend Mount Arreat. With death, however, they would be free from that duty, and be able to pass beyond. For some Barbarians however, death was not enough to end their vigil, and their spirits remained tied to the mountain, still bound to defend it. Barbarians believe(d) that if they fail(ed) to uphold their duty to Arreat, or are not given a proper burial upon its slopes, they will be denied a true warrior's death, and their spirits shall roam the land without honor for all eternity. To give one's existence to defend the mountain was considered the most honored of all sacrifices in Barbarian culture.\nBarbarians also maintain shamanistic beliefs in animal powers, which are represented through the use of totems. At least some Barbarians believe in animal spirits, and some believe in the existence of the &lt;a href=\"Unformed%20Land\"&gt;Spirit World&lt;/a&gt;. A \"Hall Beyond\" has been referenced in Barbarian culture, with the belief that those who face their end without fear will be able to keep their form in the Hall.\nFew Barbarians worship the &lt;a href=\"Light\"&gt;Light&lt;/a&gt;.\nWeaponcraft.\nBarbarians are familiar with the art of weaponsmithery, a tradition which harkens back to &lt;a href=\"Bul-Kathos\"&gt;Bul-Kathos&lt;/a&gt;. Barbarians are able to make use of weapons in ways that others simply don\u2019t possess the strength for. Heavily-muscled barbarians can also dual-wield normal weapons like swords and axes, barraging foes with multiple enchantments and weapon types at once.\nFor a time, the &lt;a href=\"swords\"&gt;sword&lt;/a&gt; was regarded as the pinnacle of Barbarian weaponcraft, though not long before the destruction of Mount Arreat, some Barbarian smiths perfected their axecraft to be the equal (or greater) weapon to that of the sword. Other tribes are dedicated to other types of weapons however, such as the &lt;a href=\"Bear%20Tribe\"&gt;Bear Tribe&lt;/a&gt; (the mace), the &lt;a href=\"Snake%20Tribe\"&gt;Snake Tribe&lt;/a&gt; (the &lt;a href=\"spear\"&gt;spear&lt;/a&gt;) and the &lt;a href=\"Crane%20Tribe\"&gt;Crane Tribe&lt;/a&gt; (the &lt;a href=\"polearm\"&gt;polearm&lt;/a&gt;). Barbarians are also capable of using thrown weapons, but few are known for their use of the &lt;a href=\"bow\"&gt;bow&lt;/a&gt;. Each tribe tells tales of their greatest weapons. While these tales differ, each tribe claims a &lt;a href=\"Blade%20of%20the%20Tribes\"&gt;certain blade&lt;/a&gt; as their own.\nKnown Tribes/Clans.\nAs of &lt;a href=\"Timeline%231285\"&gt;1285&lt;/a&gt;, there were estimated to be 32 Barbarian tribes. Each tribe can trace its ancestry back to Bul-Kathos, and each sang epic sagas of their history. With the destruction of Mount Arreat, entire tribes were wiped out from existence. Each clan paints its &lt;a href=\"warrior\"&gt;warrior&lt;/a&gt;s in a unique manner. Barbarians have a way of speaking when regarding members of a tribe (e.g. \"&lt;a href=\"Nihlathak\"&gt;Nihlathak&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=\"Crane%20Tribe\"&gt;Crane Tribe&lt;/a&gt;\")\nKnown tribes/clans include(d):\nIn-game.\nDiablo.\n\"Main article: &lt;a href=\"Barbarian%20%28Hellfire%29\"&gt;Barbarian (Hellfire)&lt;/a&gt;\"\nA Barbarian class first appeared in \"\". However, the lore of this class was of barbarians to the far south, and is unrelated to the Barbarians of later games.\nDiablo II.\n\"Main article: &lt;a href=\"Barbarian%20%28Diablo%20II%29\"&gt;Barbarian (Diablo II)&lt;/a&gt;\"\nThe Barbarian class received its first proper introduction in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\", where he was a bona fide class of his own (as opposed to the one from \"Hellfire\", who used the graphics of the &lt;a href=\"warrior\"&gt;warrior&lt;/a&gt; class), and was representative of the Children of Bul-Kathos in terms of lore. Additionally, &lt;a href=\"Barbarian%20Warrior\"&gt;Barbarian Warrior&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"hireling\"&gt;hireling&lt;/a&gt;s could be used by the player in the game's .\nDiablo III.\n\"Main article: &lt;a href=\"Barbarian%20%28Diablo%20III%29\"&gt;Barbarian (Diablo III)&lt;/a&gt;\"\nThe Barbarian class returns in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". (S)he bears resemblance to the interpretation of the character from the previous game.\nDiablo Immortal.\n\"Main article: &lt;a href=\"Barbarian%20%28Diablo%20Immortal%29\"&gt;Barbarian (Diablo Immortal)&lt;/a&gt;\"\nThe Barbarian class returns in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\". It is largely based on the character as portrayed in Diablo III.\nDiablo IV.\nThe Barbarian returns in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20IV\"&gt;Diablo IV&lt;/a&gt;\".\nNotable Barbarians.\n\"Main article: \"\nHistorical Figures.\nThe following Barbarians are/were renowned by their brethren, for their status and/or their deeds:"}
