{"id": "20788", "revid": "24916843", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=20788", "title": "Fiery Brimstone", "text": "Fiery Brimstone\u00a0was a low-level crafting material in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\", obtained by making the &lt;a href=\"Haedrig%20Eamon\"&gt;Blacksmith&lt;/a&gt; salvage legendary weapons and armor, and set items. It was also possible to find one amongst the haul of a &lt;a href=\"Rift%20Guardian\"&gt;Rift Guardian&lt;/a&gt; for players at levels 1-60. Each item with\u00a0an\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Item%20Level\"&gt;item level&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0of 1-60 salvaged would yield 1 Fiery Brimstone.\u00a0They could be stacked up to a maximum of 5000. Fiery Brimstone, along with\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Exquisite%20Essence\"&gt;Exquisite Essence&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0and\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Iridescent%20Tear\"&gt;Iridescent Tear&lt;/a&gt;, were the only crafting materials that are not\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Bind%20on%20Account\"&gt;account bound&lt;/a&gt;.\nAs of patch 2.3, they are no longer obtainable.\n\"\"&lt;a href=\"Artisans\"&gt;Artisans&lt;/a&gt; through the ages have relied on rare materials to enhance and create powerful items.\"\""}
{"id": "20247", "revid": "26096179", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=20247", "title": "Fifth Battle of the Diamond Gates", "text": "The Fifth Battle of the Diamond Gates was one of the few times the &lt;a href=\"Prime%20Evils\"&gt;Prime Evils&lt;/a&gt; truly worked together, and their combined might almost felled the &lt;a href=\"Diamond%20Gates\"&gt;gates&lt;/a&gt; leading to &lt;a href=\"Heaven\"&gt;Heaven&lt;/a&gt; itself. Just when it seemed that the Prime Evils would win the &lt;a href=\"Great%20Conflict\"&gt;Great Conflict&lt;/a&gt;, they were so confident of their impending victory that they turned on each other, fighting over spoils they had yet to win. The attack was halted as the forces of Hell battled each other, and &lt;a href=\"Izual\"&gt;Izual&lt;/a&gt; rushed to the defense of the gate, beating back the Evils and their &lt;a href=\"Demonic%20Legion\"&gt;hordes&lt;/a&gt; with his angelic runeblade &lt;a href=\"Azurewrath\"&gt;Azurewrath&lt;/a&gt;, and valiantly saving the Diamond Gates, and Heaven.\nThe &lt;a href=\"demon\"&gt;demon&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Draorm\"&gt;Draorm&lt;/a&gt; is known to have participated in this battle, along with &lt;a href=\"Tyrael\"&gt;Tyrael&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "10497", "revid": "24916843", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=10497", "title": "Fight in the nude", "text": "Fight in the nude was a popular self-imposed challenge for the original \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20%28game%29\"&gt;Diablo&lt;/a&gt;\", although it can be attempted in other games in the series as well. It involves completing the game without wearing any items. As an easier variant, one may try to beat the game without any armor, but can use weapons and jewelry.\nAlthough both Diablo and &lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;its sequel&lt;/a&gt; change character appearance based on worn armor, the TVTropes website uses \"&lt;a href=\"http%3A//tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FightInTheNude\"&gt;Fight in the Nude&lt;/a&gt;\" to describe instances where this is not true.\nIn \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\", there is a series of achievements referring to this one: these achievements are earned by killing bosses without any items equipped on the character (all damage is done by &lt;a href=\"follower\"&gt;follower&lt;/a&gt;s). The most famous of these is Naked Lust, awarded for killing &lt;a href=\"Cydaea\"&gt;Cydaea&lt;/a&gt; without any gear. These achievements can prove difficult, however; one mistake can throw the battle in the boss's favor, even with a lot of &lt;a href=\"Paragon\"&gt;Paragon&lt;/a&gt; levels. Typically, a character will use a &lt;a href=\"Crowd%20Control\"&gt;crowd-controlling&lt;/a&gt; build, with all skills aimed at keeping the boss &lt;a href=\"stun\"&gt;stunned&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"slow\"&gt;slowed&lt;/a&gt; etc.\nThe main difficulty, however, is not even the damage itself: due to the game's mechanics, a follower can only do steady damage while the character is immobile, and standing still even for a few moments may be extremely dangerous, as without equipment, not only is a hero's &lt;a href=\"Life\"&gt;Life&lt;/a&gt; very low, but his/her degree of protection is virtually nonexistent. Some classes have skills (such as &lt;a href=\"Serenity\"&gt;Serenity&lt;/a&gt;) to make them briefly immune to damage, though."}
