{"id": "2907", "revid": "154566", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2907", "title": "Fire Spells", "text": "Fire Spells is one of the &lt;a href=\"Sorceress\"&gt;Sorceress&lt;/a&gt;' three skill trees. They are generally\u00a0the most damaging of the &lt;a href=\"Sorceress\"&gt;Sorceress&lt;/a&gt; spells. Most have the ability to deal area damage. This skill tree has a few utility skills too:\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Warmth\"&gt;Warmth&lt;/a&gt;, which greatly increases the rate of mana recovery, and\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Enchant\"&gt;Enchant&lt;/a&gt;, which is a weapon buff that may be cast on mercenaries and other party members.\u00a0"}
{"id": "3457", "revid": "47915220", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=3457", "title": "Fire Tower", "text": "The Fire Tower is quite similar in its function and abilities to the &lt;a href=\"Gargoyle%20Trap\"&gt;Gargoyle Trap&lt;/a&gt;.These pyramid shaped devices shoot &lt;a href=\"fireball\"&gt;fireball&lt;/a&gt;s from their turrets. However, one can avoid being burned by moving as soon as the turret points to their direction. Fire Towers possess immense amounts of durability. &lt;a href=\"Life\"&gt;Life&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Mana\"&gt;Mana&lt;/a&gt; cannot be stolen from them, and they do not drop any items upon their destruction. They are found in &lt;a href=\"Lost%20City\"&gt;Lost City&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Valley%20of%20Snakes\"&gt;Valley of Snakes&lt;/a&gt; and various tombs. \nBackground.\nOriginally created by wary caravan traders to act as unmanned sentries, these devices soon found favor amongst anyone who was interested in safeguarding their domicile. Although they were designed to emit fireballs whenever a magical field was crossed, these fields do not seem to activate when crossed by demons. Unfortunately, this makes a Fire Tower totally ineffective as a defensive measure against the minions of Hell.\nOn Hell difficulty, Fire Towers are immune to &lt;a href=\"Poison\"&gt;Poison&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "20778", "revid": "1773829", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=20778", "title": "Fire Walkers", "text": "Fire Walkers are &lt;a href=\"Legendary%20Items\"&gt;legendary&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"boots\"&gt;boots&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". They require &lt;a href=\"character%20level\"&gt;character level&lt;/a&gt; 60 to drop.\nTheir most notable feature is leaving a short-living (about 1 second) trail of fire in the bearer's wake, much like &lt;a href=\"Blaze\"&gt;Blaze&lt;/a&gt; spell from \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\". The trail burns for 300-400% damage as Fire, and can &lt;a href=\"Critical%20Hit\"&gt;critically hit&lt;/a&gt;, but is only active while moving.\nOriginally they were created as a form of 'revenge' for players on monsters with &lt;a href=\"Monster%20Traits%20%28Diablo%20III%29\"&gt;Molten&lt;/a&gt; affixes."}
{"id": "25215", "revid": "24916843", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=25215", "title": "Fire Wall", "text": ""}
{"id": "10089", "revid": "1773829", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=10089", "title": "Fire Wall (Diablo I)", "text": "Fire Wall (a.k.a. Wall of Fire) is a spell in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20I\"&gt;Diablo I&lt;/a&gt;\".\nGeneral Information.\nFire Wall summons a wall of flame that exists for a period of time. During this time, any being foolish enough to enter the flames will suffer Fire damage. The higher the level of the character, the higher the damage, and the higher the spell level, the longer the wall will last. Multiple firewalls do stack in effectiveness. Length of the wall does not change with levels.\nIt does deal damage to the character, if they enter it, which limits its effectiveness: one has to carefully position themselves and the enemy to keep the foes in the wall (most enemies do not attempt to escape the wall except for to chase the character). Most monsters will not advance \"into\" the flames, SPOILER! but this AI can be used against them: casting a Fire Wall in front of them, and then casting one on top of them, will make enemies stand and roast, since they're not smart enough to move backwards out of the fire. SPOILER!!! This is a very popular way to kill himself.\nThe spell can prove useful for a first time encounter with the first \"&lt;a href=\"Boss\"&gt;boss&lt;/a&gt;\" of the game, &lt;a href=\"The%20Butcher%20%28Diablo%20I%29\"&gt;the Butcher&lt;/a&gt;. The reason for this is that as the player is usually at a low level, even with the installed, even the toughest of heroes will have a hard time successfully surviving the Butcher's relentless and powerful attacks.\nAs multiple Firewalls can be stacked on top of each other, increasing the damage proportionally, this spell is very useful against monsters stuck on the other side of an obstacle.\nThe central sprite of the firewall (the casting point) does double damage. If Firewall damages the player who casts it, this damage is treated as a Trap (thus \"of thieves\" item will halve it) and is not &lt;a href=\"block\"&gt;block&lt;/a&gt;able. Each space in the flame hits every .05 second for the duration.\nDamage Calculation:\nLore.\n\"Magical fire feeds upon no earthly source, being fueled instead by the mystic energies known as Mana. While the heat of conjured flames may cause normal matter to combust and burn on its own, the flames themselves will burn as long they have Mana to draw upon. By carefully controlling the flow of Mana to a magical fire, its life-span can be extended well beyond that of a &lt;a href=\"Firebolt\"&gt;Firebolt&lt;/a&gt; or an &lt;a href=\"Inferno\"&gt;Inferno&lt;/a&gt;. The &lt;a href=\"Horadrim\"&gt;Horadrim&lt;/a&gt; were skilled enough to create torches that burn with an eternal flame, but those abilities have been long lost. With this spell, the caster creates a wall of eldritch flame that will burn until the Mana in that area has been exhausted. As knowledge of this spell increases, the rate at which Mana must be consumed can be better controlled and the Wall of Fire can be made to burn longer.\""}
{"id": "2968", "revid": "1773829", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2968", "title": "Fire Wall (Diablo II)", "text": "Fire Wall is a &lt;a href=\"Sorceress\"&gt;Sorceress&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Skill\"&gt;Skill&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\".\nLore.\n\"This skill allows the Sorceress to raise a barrier of flame to block her flanks from attack, creating a tactical advantage for both herself and her allies. Any creature unwitting enough to attempt to cross the barrier will feel the full force of these flames as they advance to their ruin. \"\nIn-game.\nFire Wall creates a wall of fire in a horizontal line in front of the caster. Its damage per second and its length increase with more levels. Fire Wall is arguably the highest damaging spell in the &lt;a href=\"Sorceress\"&gt;Sorceress&lt;/a&gt;' arsenal. It deals massive damage, and if used correctly it can take down most foes instantly or fairly quickly. Multiple Fire Walls stack damage, though not too many can be stacked due to a short &lt;a href=\"Casting%20Delay\"&gt;Casting Delay&lt;/a&gt; and limited duration.\nSkill Progression.\nDuration: 3.6 seconds\nThe \"Radius\" (renamed to \"Range\" in \"\", i.e. wall length) values provided by the tooltip are invalid, because D2LoD had a bug which resulted in the length of the flames being always 4/3 yards bigger than described (base missile range was assumed 5 but was actually 7), which was then ported into D2R. Even if this bug weren't present, this value would still be only an approximation of what really happens due to difference in diagonal vs. horizontal/vertical walls; those values are very close to the \"range from tooltip + 4/3 yards\" value though.\nStrategy.\nDue to its low synergies, Fire Wall is often utilized in &lt;a href=\"build\"&gt;build&lt;/a&gt;s (most notably the &lt;a href=\"Fire%20Wall%20Sorceress\"&gt;Fire Wall Sorceress&lt;/a&gt;) since it can be easily combined with other skills without having to sink too many points into associated skills to maximize its damage potential. However, even though it doesn't synergize well, it is still incredibly powerful, especially with &lt;a href=\"Fire%20Mastery\"&gt;Fire Mastery&lt;/a&gt;. The only problems are its rather limited mobility, its cooldown, and high Mana cost, and the fact that swift enemies and human players can often avoid it with ease.\nUsing Fire Wall on the other side of valleys, rivers and other obstacles can cause monsters to bunch up and take heavy damage. Laying down some Fire Walls, then leading monsters into it is a useful defensive application of Fire Wall. Another tactic to keep monsters within the wall is to run in circles around the areas of Fire Wall, until the Monsters within die. Monsters distracted by minions or party members can fall easy prey to Fire Walls. This works especially well with something like a &lt;a href=\"Golem\"&gt;Golem&lt;/a&gt; which attracts monsters. Some fast and erratically moving monsters, however, will generally avoid the Fire Wall.\nFrequent users of high level Fire Walls often learn to place the wall immediately next to their Sorceress, perpendicular to the direction of an enemy. With this orientation, the Wall actually extends directly toward the enemy, and the Sorceress is only a step a way from the Wall herself, thereby luring the enemy to walk down the entire length of the wall. &lt;a href=\"Teleport%20%28Diablo%20II%29\"&gt;Teleport&lt;/a&gt; can be used when the enemy nears the same end as the Sorceress to lead the enemy back along the Wall the other way. "}
{"id": "11729", "revid": "865253", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11729", "title": "Fire Wall (Diablo I Spell)", "text": ""}
{"id": "11955", "revid": "13298744", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11955", "title": "Fire Wall (monster skill)", "text": "Fire Wall is a monster skill usually wielded by &lt;a href=\"Vampire\"&gt;Vampire&lt;/a&gt;s in &lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;, but the main antagonist of the game, &lt;a href=\"Diablo\"&gt;Diablo&lt;/a&gt; himself, uses this skill as well. Fire Wall works the same as and looks identical to the &lt;a href=\"Sorceress\"&gt;Sorceress&lt;/a&gt; spell &lt;a href=\"Fire%20Wall%20%28Diablo%20II%29\"&gt;of the same name&lt;/a&gt;; it deals &lt;a href=\"Fire%20Damage\"&gt;Fire Damage&lt;/a&gt; in an area of effect."}
{"id": "8070", "revid": "154566", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=8070", "title": "Fire Wall Sorceress", "text": "The Fire Wall Sorceress is a &lt;a href=\"Sorceress\"&gt;Sorceress&lt;/a&gt; build that focuses on the Fire Wall Spell.\nFire Wall is a fascinating spell: although it does immense amounts of damage, especially when combined with the high bonus of Fire Mastery, it also has no synergy. As a result, the Fire Wall Sorceress can easily uphold her expertise with other skills.\nSince V1.13 the Fire Wall ability now has a synergy with both Warmth (4% damage per point) and Inferno (1% damage per point). As such it is no longer devoid of synergies. However the low boost granted by inferno and the usefulness of Warmth means it's still viable to use with other skills.\nWhen leveled up high enough, Fire Wall can do thousands of damage per second. The only problem is that Fire Wall, for one, deals damage over time in a set area. If an opponent is smart enough, they will avoid the Fire Wall and avoid death, or simply walk out of the fire without sustaining full damage from the spell. As a result, the Fire Wall Sorceress is not very useful in PvP, since most opposing players will simply step out of its way.\nAdditionally, most enemies in mode are immune to fire. Therefore, Fire Wall Sorceresses often choose to create a more versatile character:\nOne possible build is to combine the firewall build with an enchantress, creating a true party sorceress, buffing allies then using them as tanks to hold the enemy still. After maxing warmth, firewall, enchant and fire mastery there's still enough points to put into frozen orb or other low synergy skills. As such this build is a highly competent party build with decent solo ability, more than enough to walk through nightmare and with decent gear and a strong build can happily survive through hell alone.\nSince the Fire Wall Sorceress is often hybridized, finding equipment could be difficult; since Fire Wall is their spell of choice, finding + Fire equipment such as &lt;a href=\"Eschuta%27s%20Temper\"&gt;Eschuta's Temper&lt;/a&gt; is often preferred, but depending on what other spells are used, other elemental equipment or equipment that gives + to all skills may be more effective."}
{"id": "54006", "revid": "46404728", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=54006", "title": "Fire and Ash", "text": "Fire and Ash is a &lt;a href=\"mount\"&gt;mount&lt;/a&gt; set in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20IV\"&gt;Diablo IV&lt;/a&gt;\". It is part of the &lt;a href=\"Ash%20Knight\"&gt;Ash Knight&lt;/a&gt; cosmetic theme, and it costs 2000 &lt;a href=\"platinum\"&gt;platinum&lt;/a&gt;."}
